message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The quadruple screening test measures alpha-fetoprotein, beta-HCG, estriol, and inhibin A. In this case, only the alpha-fetoprotein is markedly elevated, which is associated with spina bifida cystica. Trisomy 21 and 18, as well as holoprosencephaly, would not cause a marked elevation in alpha-fetoprotein. The patient's alcohol consumption may also contribute to the risk of spina bifida.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The elevated maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein level suggests an open neural tube defect, which is most commonly seen in spina bifida cystica. Trisomy 21 and Trisomy 18 are not typically associated with increased alpha-fetoprotein levels. Holoprosencephaly is associated with abnormalities in estriol and inhibin A levels in addition to alpha-fetoprotein abnormalities.

Trisomy 21 and Trisomy 18 are associated with abnormal levels of all four markers on the quadruple screen. Holoprosencephaly is associated with abnormal levels of β-human chorionic gonadotropin and inhibin A, not α-fetoprotein.
